posts.text:
网易娱乐11月7日报道 秋冬已上线，立冬不剧荒!万众期待的2017热血逐梦纵横职场年度压轴钜制《猎场》，昨日在长沙举行了看片会。陈龙、胡兵、菅纫姿、章龄之、徐阁等众位主演悉数到场，并与观众们热情互动。看片结束后，胡歌满脸笑容地来到现场接受媒体提问，一上来就关切地问大家吃了没，随后用一句“反正我吃了”活跃全场气氛，在轻松的状态中，胡歌也透露出不少关于《猎场》和自己的小秘密。
演员胡歌明年“上岗” 希望大家更喜欢自己出演的角色
从今年年初赴美留学，胡歌已经在大众视野中消失了许久，媒体代表万分想念的“胡椒”问出了大家最关心的问题，“什么时候回归？”。胡歌坦言，“我在演员这个岗位之外晃了太久，明年该回来上班了”。此话一出，现场的粉丝们兴奋不已，纷纷表示“你终于知道回来了”、“期待老胡的回归”。
不得不说胡歌离开的这段时间真的是让大家思念如狂，而《猎场》作为霸屏级电视剧《伪装者》《琅琊榜》之后胡歌唯一接下的片约，它的播出无疑让等待老胡回归的日子有“秋冬”哥的陪伴。在被问道“如果看了剧我们喜欢郑秋冬胜过喜欢你，你会吃醋吗”？胡歌则淡定地表示“不会，非常希望大家能够更喜欢我演的角色，支持《猎场》”。
“秋冬”上身难以出戏，和张嘉译对戏压力最大
采访中，胡歌丝毫不掩饰自己对郑秋冬这个角色的喜爱，他认为演员最大的意义就在于可以用一辈子的时间尝试几辈子的人生，而“郑秋冬身上体验很多不同的命运，感觉过了几辈子的人生，这也是这个角色的魅力所在。”在《猎场》中，郑秋冬以完完全全的草根形象出现，经历多次起起伏伏，如何从打击中爬起来，走到更高的地方非常考验演技。
而看片会现场播出的两集内容中可以看出，胡歌完美诠释出了郑秋冬在两个不同人生阶段——一个懵懂无知、对未来没有规划，一个眼神坚定、充满了事业的野心，搭档孙红雷和张嘉译两位戏骨，出神入化的演技令媒体赞叹不已。对此，胡歌坦言：“其实和张嘉译老师对戏的时候最有压力。”还补充到，“在《猎场》杀青之后我觉得郑秋冬这个人迟迟没有离开，或者说我不愿意他离开”。

posts.text:
07.11.2017 Toyota legt im Halbjahr zu Toyota-Produktion im japanischen Toyota. Der Konzern hat die Prognose für das noch bis Ende März 2018 laufende Gesamtgeschäftsjahr angehoben. Everett Kennedy Brown Tokio dpa Japans größter Autobauer Toyota hat den Nettogewinn in der ersten Hälfte des laufenden Geschäftsjahres erhöht. Wie der Volkswagen-Rivale nach Börsenschluss bekanntgab, fiel zwischen April und September unter dem Strich ein Ertrag von 1,07 Billionen Yen an (rund 8 Mrd Euro). 
Das ist ein Zuwachs von 13,2 Prozent im Vergleich zum Vorjahreszeitraum. Der Umsatz stieg um 8,6 Prozent auf 14,19 Billionen Yen. Das Unternehmen, zu dem auch die Nutzfahrzeugtochter Hino Motors und der Kleinwagenbauer Daihatsu gehören, hob die Prognose für das noch bis Ende März 2018 laufende Gesamtgeschäftsjahr dank des schwachen Yen an und rechnet nun mit 1,95 Billionen Yen Gewinn statt wie bisher mit 1,75 Billionen.

posts.text: Inicio » Atlántica XXII » Gregorio Morán presenta en Oviedo la reedición de ‘Miseria y grandeza del PCE’ Gregorio Morán presenta en Oviedo la reedición de ‘Miseria y grandeza del PCE’   7, 2017 Tweet El periodista ovetense Gregorio Morán. El periodista Gregorio Morán presenta hoy en Oviedo el libro Miseria, grandeza y agonía del PCE , edición revisada y actualizada de su ya clásica historia del Partido Comunista de España. El acto, que dará comienzo a las 20 horas, tendrá lugar en el edificio Pavo Real del Campo de San Francisco y será presentado por el periodista Xuan Cándano, director de ATLÁNTICA XXII, con la presencia del economista José Feito. Está organizado por Foro Abierto. Hace justo ahora tres décadas veía la luz Miseria y grandeza del Partido Comunista de España (1939-1985) , una obra mítica dedicada “a los militantes anónimos que murieron por la libertad y que no tienen tumba, ni familia, ni partido que los recuerde”. Gregorio Morán era un antiguo comunista que había conocido el exilio en sus propias carnes y el libro todo un legado personal y biográfico del autor, que formó parte activa de la propia historia del PCE y vivió en primera fila la Transición. La nueva edición revisada y actualizada está publicada por Akal. Del periodista ovetense, verdadero azote de la cultura y la política españolas de los últimos cuarenta años, poco cabe añadir que no sea de público dominio. Colaborador de ATLÁNTICA XXII desde la fundación de la revista, sus libros constituyen magnos «ajustes de cuentas» –en el mejor de los sentidos– con la intelectualidad y con la historia contemporánea españolas. Morán ha revisitado una y otra vez los hitos de nuestro pasado inmediato para arrojar una luz descarnada sobre los grandes y –aparentemente– férreos e inamovibles consensos de la cultura española, ofreciendo de los mismos una imagen, si no tan favorecida como la oficial, indudablemente sí más justa. Recientemente fue despedido de La Vanguardia de Barcelona, diario en el que colaboraba desde hacía casi treinta años, tras haberle sido censurada la última de sus colaboraciones habituales en el periódico.

posts.text: Waitotara crash victim was 'friendly, giving' Canadian nanny 7 Nov, 2017 7:00pm 2 minutes to read Canadian Angelika Melisa Loukas, a 'nanny' in Waitotara, died after this crash in the early hours of Sunday, October 29 Wanganui Chronicle The father of a 21-year-old au pair living with a Whanganui family rushed over from their home in Canada when he heard his daughter had been in a car crash. Angelika Melisa Loukas died following the crash on Waitotara Valley Rd in the early hours of Sunday. Loukas, who lived in Waitotara Valley with her host family, was in the vehicle when it lost control and careered about 100m down a steep hill. She suffered critical injuries and was flown to Wellington Hospital about 90 minutes after the crash, reports Fairfax. She died from her injuries two days later. Advertisement Advertise with NZME. A 25-year-old Whanganui man was also injured in the crash, which police are investigating. Speaking to Fairfax from Canada, her mother Anne Loukas said Angelika's father Gus Loukas rushed to New Zealand upon hearing the news. He later video-called a group of devastated friends and family, including Angelika's 19-year-old sister Athena and her 22-year-old brother Theodore. Anne said the family had initially been told Angelika was in a stable condition, but she didn't make it. "But by the time I got home, the neurosurgeon talking to my husband said she didn't make it," she said. Her daughter was affectionately known as "Baba" (Greek for "baby") by her family and had come to New Zealand in May. "She always wanted to travel and she was always talking about New Zealand." Back in Canada she had been studying psychology at the University of Ottawa, but had decided to take a break to live with a Whanganui family and work as an au pair. "She loved the boys and the mum was like her best friend," Anne told Fairfax. Anne said Angelika had bonded with the young boys and her host parents Daniel Mccoll and Alice White. Angelika was a friendly, outgoing girl who had loved New Zealand. "As a middle child, she would give everything she had to make other people happy." Angelika's body has been cremated and taken back to Ottawa in Ontario.

posts.text:
全台湾最难订位的餐厅是哪1家？答案是汉来海港餐厅，一开放订位就秒杀，热门时段更是一位难求，让这家自助餐厅成为不少人跃跃欲试的口袋名单。素有「南霸天」之称的高雄汉来大饭店海港餐厅，近年来一路挥军北上，在国内餐饮业中最红海的市场，开创出新蓝海，为餐饮市场写下1页传奇。 
其中背后的推手就是汉来美食总经理林淑婷。林淑婷讲起话来很有「妈妈味」，同事对她的形容就是「龟毛、挑剔的处女座」；当年从宴会厅的业务经理做起，因为服务很到位，抓住不少政商名流的心，因而受到大老板赏识，在汉来饭店分割餐饮业务时，担起重任。 
料理研究发展 走在最前端 
「爸爸是大厨师，小时候常常东西炸出来，都还没放到盘子里，就已经被我们吃掉了。」或许身为厨师之女，林淑婷对于美食特别敏锐，她常常带着厨师到香港、澳门、上海研究菜色，「有时候1天吃6餐，时间太短都要用跑的。」 
林淑婷说，自助餐不只是做自助餐，而是各国料理都要去看，研究发展一定要走在业界前面。像以前自助餐的重点是日本料理区，讲究生鱼片；现在进化了，还要有温寿司，菜色必须与时俱进。设备自然也不能马虎，以前海港餐厅因为在饭店里面，还要做早餐，不会为了出披萨而做1个烤炉；但现在开出去的店就有烤炉，1台都要价上百万元。林淑婷表示，汉来海港餐厅不是一般的自助餐，而是9个主题餐厅，料理全部是现场制作，因此，每一家店需要45至47位厨师，高雄巨蛋店的厨师甚至多达70位。 
不同于一般餐厅分内外场，厨师管厨房、外场有经理，海港餐厅每家店的店长都是厨师。林淑婷说，一般餐厅都是外场经理反映客人意见给厨师，厨师却不这么认为：「客人不懂啦!我做的菜就是最好吃的，你要不要吃，我不管。」但是海港餐厅的厨师就是店长，要走出来服务客人，亲自看看哪几道菜为什么都没人吃？ 
汉来美食海港餐厅的生意好，林淑婷认为，答案就是CP值高。由于汉来美食旗下餐厅多，有共同採购的规模效益，因此成本能够有效控制，订价比5星级饭店便宜，消费者自然趋之若鹜。「当初海港上来台北在敦南SOGO开店，我带同事去台北住了一星期，四处观察反覆研究，就是为了订价。」...

posts.text: وزارة المالية السعودية تكشف حقيقة تعديل رسوم الوافدين بالمملكة الثلاثاء 07/نوفمبر/2017 - 10:48 ص الفجر السعودي نفت وزارة المالية السعودية، الاثنين، ما تناقلته وسائل الإعلام من مزاعم عن توجه الحكومة لإجراء تعديلات على برنامج المقابل المالي على الوافدين والمرافقين. وقالت الوزارة في بيان لها، أن المقابل المالي على الوافدين ومرافقيهم وفق ما أعُلن سابقا، لم يطرأ عليه أي تعديل، مؤكدة أنها لم تعلن عن أي تأجيل ولم تدل بأية تصريحات بهذا الخصوص. كما نقلت "روسيا اليوم" وبدأت السلطات السعودية اعتبارا من أول يوليو 2017 في تطبيق ضريبة على "المرافقين والمرافقات" للعمالة الوافدة، والتي أقرها مجلس الوزراء ضمن برنامج التوازن المالي. وسيتم تحصيل الرسوم عن المرافقين عند تجديد هوية المقيم، بواقع 100 ريال كرسم شهري على كل مرافق للعمالة الوافدة في السعودية، ليصبح المبلغ سنويا 1200 ريال، ويتضاعف المبلغ في تموز يوليو 2018، حتى يصل في يوليو 2020 إلى 400 ريال في الشهر وبمجموع 4800 ريال في العام. وأضافت أن ما جاء في تصريحات وزير المالية محمد الجدعان خلال اليومين السابقين، تتحدث عن تعديلات محتملة سيتم تطبيقها على برنامج التوازن المالي، مشيرة إلى أن تلك التعديلات سيتم الإعلان عنها قبل إعلان ميزانية 2018. وأوضحت الوزارة أن تصريحات الوزير فسرت بشكل خاطئ حول برنامج التوازن المالي. كما أشارت إلى أن الوزير بيّن أن الوصول إلى التوازن الصفري بحلول العام 2020 ليس هدفا، وإنما الهدف هو الوصول إلى إصلاح مالي مستدام في المدى المتوسط. ونوهت الوزارة بأنه يمكن تمديد التوازن المالي حتى العام المالي 2023، للمحافظة على نسبة نمو مناسبة، مشيرة إلى أن مؤشرات الأداء للعام 2018م يتوقع أن تكون إيجابية بشكل أكبر.

posts.title: Taranaki crash victim was 'friendly, giving' Canadian nanny
posts.text: Taranaki crash victim was 'friendly, giving' Canadian nanny 7 Nov, 2017 5:47pm 3 minutes to read The woman who died after a crash in Taranaki was Canadian national Angelika Melisa Loukas. Photo / Supplied NZ Herald The father of a 21-year-old au pair living with a Whanganui family rushed over from their home in Canada when he heard his daughter had been in a car crash. Angelika Melisa Loukas died following the crash on Waitotara Valley Rd in the early hours of Sunday. Loukas, who lived in Waitotara Valley with her host family, was in the vehicle when it lost control and careered about 100m down a steep hill. Waverley fire chief Alan Hickford confirmed to the Herald on the weekend that another occupant in the car walked around 3km to find help for Loukas. Advertisement Advertise with NZME. He had walked past two houses he didn't see in the pitch black, before he finally managed to call for help about 4.20am. Hickford said the man had no idea where the crash occurred and it was simply a case of firefighters using their nous and spotting any suspicious clues along the side of Waitotara Valley Rd that led them to finding his injured female friend. He described the hill as being "very, very steep" and after finding the injured woman firefighters carried her about a further 100m to the waiting rescue chopper. Loukas suffered critical injuries and was flown to Wellington Hospital about 90 minutes after the crash, reports Fairfax. She died from her injuries two days later. Police said a male occupant from the vehicle was also injured in the crash, which they are investigating. Speaking to Fairfax from Canada, her mother Anne Loukas said Angelika's father Gus Loukas rushed to New Zealand upon hearing the news. He later video-called a group of devastated friends and family, including Angelika's 19-year-old sister Athena and her 22-year-old brother Theodore. Anne said the family had initially been told Angelika was in a stable condition, but she didn't make it. "But by the time I got home, the neurosurgeon talking to my husband said she didn't make it," she said. Her daughter was affectionately known as "Baba" (Greek for "baby") by her family and had come to New Zealand in May. "She always wanted to travel and she was always talking about New Zealand." Back in Canada she had been studying psychology at the University of Ottawa, but had decided to take a break to live with a Whanganui family and work as an au pair. "She loved the boys and the mum was like her best friend," Anne told Fairfax. Anne said Angelika had bonded with the young boys and her host parents Daniel Mccoll and Alice White. Angelika was a friendly, outgoing girl who had loved New Zealand. "As a middle child, she would give everything she had to make other people happy." Angelika's body has been cremated and taken back to Ottawa in Ontario.

posts.author: PamyLotta (noreply@blogger.com)
posts.title: Lebenszeichen
posts.text:
Eigentlich hab ich im Moment ja keine Zeit. Zu nichts. Nicht mal zum Bloggen (was Grund dafür ist, warum es hier in den letzten Wochen so still geworden ist - also mach Dir keine Sorgen, alles gut bei mir). Oder nicht mal zum kurz Anhalten für ein schönes Foto. Immer aufm Sprung - immer im Stress.   Und dann fahr ich heute morgen zur Arbeit (spät dran, deshalb schon hell und dann noch auf einem  meiner Schleichwege, weil mal wieder auf meinem normalen Weg ne Baustelle eingerichtet ist) und sehe ihn. Diesen herrlichen Skelettbaum. Wenn Du schon länger bei mir mitliest, weißt Du ja bereits, dass ich dafür nen absoluten Faible habe.  Doch gleichzeitig wird mir dabei auch bewusst, dass ich vor lauter Stress den schönen bunten  Herbst verpasst habe. Keine Herbstspaziergänge, kein Pilze, Blätter, Eicheln, Kastanien oder sonstig schöne Sachen sammeln. Einfach so an mir vorbeigegangen - und zwar komplett.   

Dafür gibt's jetzt wieder Skelettbäume. Die mag ich ja eh noch viel mehr - dieses Grau und auch die herrlich aufziehenden Nebelschwaden auf den Feldern. Etwas, das sicher nicht Jedermanns Sache ist, aber ich lieb das eben  total. 

So konnte ich heute frühs dann nicht anders, ich musste einfach anhalten (spät dran war ich ja eh schon), um schnell das Foto zu machen. Und dann fiel mir ein -nachdem ich jetzt schon ein paar Mails und Nachrichten bekommen habe, ob bei mir alles gut ist- , dass es definitiv auch an der Zeit ist, mal wieder hier ein Lebenszeichen zu hinterlassen und zu sagen, dass ich bald zurückkomme. Denn die Stressphase ist bald vorbei. Ganz bald.    Was genau dahintersteckt, verrate ich Dir aber ein anderes Mal, denn es ist wirklich einiges passiert im Hause Pamylotta - aber das ist dann schon ein eigener Post wert ;)

                                                                                     ***
Pamy

posts.title: Whanganui right fit for new Sarjeant Gallery staffer
posts.text: Whanganui right fit for new Sarjeant Gallery staffer 7 Nov, 2017 6:00pm 3 minutes to read The Sarjeant Gallery's new relationships officer is loving the pace of life in Whanganui. Photo/ Bevan Conley By: Liz Wylie, Share on Reddit reddit Jaki Arthur was stuck in traffic in the back seat of a Sydney taxi when she got a call from Whanganui. Ms Arthur learned that she was short-listed for the position of relationships officer with the Sarjeant Gallery and rather than conduct an online interview, she decided to jump on a plane. "I just felt so attracted to Whanganui and had to come and see it for myself. "My daughter Marianne and I flew to Wellington, hired a car and drove here for the interview. "Driving in across the City Bridge - we fell in love." Although she was born in Christchurch and grew up in Auckland, Ms Arthur said she had never visited Whanganui. "After leaving school, I enrolled to do an arts degree at Auckland University and got a weekend job at Unity Books. "My part-time job became my career and I learned so much from Nigel Cox at Unity. "He encouraged me to read everything in the shop - from science books to theology and I have pretty much worked in publishing ever since." Ms Arthur spent four years in London working as a freelance publicist and had a circus as one of her clients. She also spent time working on a boat in France. Working for publishing companies Random House and Hodder Publishing in Australia was great she says, but life in Sydney was becoming too fast-paced and did not suit her family. Her family of consists of 13 year-old daughter Marianne and 85 year-old mother Doreen. The school Marianne was attending in Bondi had a huge roll and Ms Arthur says her daughter is enjoying attending Wanganui Collegiate and making new friends, while her mother is also enjoying life in Whanganui. "Mum enjoyed staying with a family in Waverley when she was a child so she already knew she liked this region. "We had talked about moving back to New Zealand and everything just seemed to fall into place." The family have also purchased a house in Whanganui and Ms Arthur said it is a home they love. "We saw it when we came for my interview and when we returned to Sydney it was taken off the market. "When we were ready to move here, it was back on the market so it seems like it was meant to be our home." Ms Arthur's newly created public relations role at the Sarjeant is one she is very much enjoying after her first three weeks she says. "I think the Sarjeant is such a wonderful asset and I am really enjoying working with the team and looking forward to the exciting developments ahead," she says. Ms Arthur's role will grow as the Sarjeant continues to seek support from corporates, small business, individuals, philanthropists and charitable trusts for the ongoing care of the collection.
